    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key TakeAway}</m>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-mass-weight">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Weight</alert> is the measure of the force of gravity acting on an object.
            </p>
            <p>
                The SI unit of weight is the <alert>newton</alert> (N).
            </p>
            <p>
                Weight (W) <m>=</m> mass of an object (kg) <m> \times</m> gravitational force (N/kg)
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
        <p>
            Planets in the solar system have different gravitational forces.
            This means that the weight of an object will vary depending on the planet it is on,
            but its mass will remain constant.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example, the gravitational field strength on Earth is approximately <m>10</m> N/kg, 
            which means that an object with a mass of <m>4</m> kg will weigh <m>40</m> N on Earth.
        </p>
    </remark>
